Haldir,

As I understand it, the C++ standard prohibits use of &#39;__&#39; to start 
identifier names in the global namespace, and in namespace &#39;std&#39;, but 
not in other ones (e.g. Cantera).  But it seems Microsoft C++ may be 
more restrictive about this.  (I think you can turn off the Microsoft 
C++ extensions with a compiler flag.)

That having been said, I think it is true that it is now considered bad 
style to begin names with an underscore, single or double.  It used to 
be ok, and the widely-used &quot;Design Patterns&quot; book does this quite a 
bit.  I wrote &quot;utilities.h&quot; when I was reading Design Patterns, and 
adopted their notation.  But to avoid problems, I&#39;ll see if I can 
remove leading underscores from names in Cantera. Fortunately they are 
only used in a few places.

Dave



